Boston_DescriptiveStatistics

Roxana Butenco

18 June 2019

In this document well look at the dataset in more detail and will seek significant predictors in relation to crime. Will look at the correlation between all variables to analyse each correlation coefficient, getting a first impression of the relationship between them. At the moment the goal is to find what kind of regression modelling, if any, can be applied to data for better crime prediction (for example if linear trends are visible, we may fit a linear regression model).

Specify the working directory and read in data from a csv file:

setwd("~/RDemo/BostonRegression")
Boston = read.csv(file="Boston.csv",header=TRUE,sep=",")
#library(MASS)
#attach(Boston)
data("Boston")
#View(Boston) #invoke the data viewer that also contain some basic exploratory features
#fix(Boston) #open a quick data editor
#??Boston #get familliar with the dataset from its original source

Correlation matrix visualization with Pearson correlation coefficient

#install.packages("ggcorrplot") 
#if(!require(devtools)) install.packages("devtools")
#devtools::install_github("kassambara/ggcorrplot")
library(ggcorrplot)
#library(ggplot2)
corr <- round(cor(Boston), 1)
ggcorrplot(corr, lab=TRUE, hc.order = TRUE, outline.col = "white", type = "full", ggtheme = ggplot2::theme_gray,
           colors = c("#6D9EC1", "white", "#E46726"))

Correlation matrix visualization with Pearson correlation coefficient Predictor variables correlation chart

chart.Correlation(Boston, histogram=TRUE, pch=19)

Boston %>%
  gather(-crim, key = "var", value = "value") %>%
  filter(var != "chas") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = value, y = crim)) +
  geom_point() +
  stat_smooth() +
  facet_wrap(~ var, scales = "free") +
  theme_bw()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Predictors histograms less chas:

Boston %>% 
  gather(-crim, key = "var", value = "value") %>%
  filter(var != "chas") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = value)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_wrap(~ var, scales = "free") +
  theme_bw()

Boxplots and a closer look at crim and zn:

my_data <- Boston[, c(1,2)]
chart.Correlation(my_data, histogram=TRUE, pch=19)

Boston %>% #Predictors boxplots -chas where we can clearly see the outliers 
  gather(-crim, key = "var", value = "value") %>%
  filter(var != "chas") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = '',y = value)) +
  geom_boxplot(outlier.colour = "red", outlier.shape = 1) +
  facet_wrap(~ var, scales = "free") +
  theme_grey()

Is the correlation between zone and crim statistically significant:

ggplot(data=Boston)+
   geom_point(mapping = aes(x=zn, y=crim)) +
    theme_bw()

cor.test(Boston$zn,Boston$crim)#
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  Boston$zn and Boston$crim
## t = -4.5938, df = 504, p-value = 5.506e-06
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.2826979 -0.1153156
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## -0.2004692

By looking at the above plot and correlation coefficient, it doesnt seem there is much correlation between zn and crim, or at least its not statistically significant.

In conclusion, our response variable crim has a moderate uphill relationship with rad, tax, lstat (e.g.with a unit change in rad, crim increases), a week positive relationship with nox, indus and age and it has a week negative relation with medv, black and dis (crim increases as medv decreases). Crim shows almost no linear relationship with ptratio, rm and zn and the correlation doesnt mean much in these cases. So, the only safe conclusion here is that a linear trend may exist between rad, tax, lstat, nox, indus, age, medv, black, dis and crim.

## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

In conclusion, our response variable crim has a moderate uphill relationship with rad, tax, lstat (e.g.with a unit change in rad, crim increases), a week positive relationship with nox, indus and age and it has a week negative relation with medv, black and dis (crim increases as medv decreases). Crim shows almost no linear relationship with ptratio, rm and zn and the correlation doesnt mean much in these cases. So, the only safe conclusion here is that a linear trend may exist between rad, tax, lstat, nox, indus, age, medv, black, dis and crim.
